Set Up

load("nba_data.rda") # Load data

The dataset we are using contains statistics on NBA games from 2010 to 2021, the features in the data are:

The statistics calculated are:

  • fgm - Field goals made
  • fga - Field goals attempted
  • fg3m - 3 point shots made
  • fg3a - 3 point shots attempted
  • fg2m - 2 point shots made
  • fg2a - 2 point shots attempted
  • ftm - Free throws made
  • fta - Free throws attempted
  • oreb - Offensive rebounds
  • dreb - Defensive rebounds
  • treb - Total rebounds
  • ast - Assists
  • stl - Steals
  • blk - Blocks
  • tov - Turnovers
  • pf - Personal fouls
  • pts - Points scored
  • pctfg - Field goal percentage
  • pctfg2 - 2 point field goal percentage
  • pctfg3 - 3 point field goal percentage
  • pctft - Free throw percentage

These are calculated for the different aspects of the matchup denoted by the following adjustments to the variable names:

  • _1_off - Offensive stats for team 1 in previous games
  • _1_def - Defensive stats for team 1 in previous games (That is stats from team 1âs opponents)
  • _2_off - Offensive stats for team 2 in previous games
  • _2_def - Defensive stats for team 2 in previous games (That is stats from team 2âs opponents)

There is also an ELO rating function which can be used to provide a ranking of the teams:

https://medium.com/purple-theory/what-is-elo-rating-c4eb7a9061e0

The objective of our analysis is to determine the key factors involved in winning NBA games, so we will use point differential as our response variable.

# Create response variable
nba_data$point_diff <- nba_data$team_1_points - nba_data$team_2_points

Before running the model we want to drop all of the unique identifiers for the games and the points used to calculate the differential:

# Drop columns 
nba_model <- nba_data[,c(8:91, 94:96)]

g_1

I see a mirrored density graph (this is due to the data having repeat games). However if we ignore the mirroring we realize most of the values are between 0 and 30 (with a peak between 1-10) and then the right tail (for the values greater than 0) extends all the way to 60. This hints at a right skewed distribution

Also it is important to note games cannot finish at 0 as it goes to over time this is due to the duplication of games

Once again we see the some sort of mirror effect since point difference is involved but not symmetrical. We can see an extremely small hint of an increasing trend however it is very hard to see. The relationship does not seem significant as a lone predictor. This slightly hints at the idea that as the elo gets higher point diff increases (slight +ve).

The addition of the interaction terms took significance from elo_1, ast_1_def, stl_1_off, and dreb_1_off (all the terms included in the creation of the interaction terms.) making it no longer significant at the 0.1% level. This left only tov_1_off, ast_2_def and elo_2 as significant predictors at the 0.1% level. It is also important to note tht the interaction terms them selves are not significant.

Moreover, the addition of the terms caused stl_1_off sign to flipped to -ve and ast_1_def sign to flip to +ve.

As for values, there were slight changes but as for the significant predictors the changes were not extreme.

Lastly, the R-squared did not change after said additions thus no effect on the fit, they just made the model more complex (might be better to leave them out)
